Note that a total of 4410 NA records that associated with 4 variables
Two solutions:
1. Replace missing values. Latitude, longitude and zip code can be identified from the address field
2. Omission. The remaining 4 variables will be removed in the following processes. Variables that are still missing: Wards, Census Tracts, Community Areas & Historical Wards 2003-2015.
So the team decide to remove 4410 missing record rows since the team cannot find more information to fill these blanks.

WNV<- WNV[!is.na(WNV$Wards),]

Partitioning datasets

Convert RESULT from positive,negaetive into 1,0 in order to get better result in lift chart.

WNV$isPos <- 1 * (WNV$RESULT == "positive")

The variables the team decide to remove:
1. TEST.ID - unique each row(0.99 cor with year), explained before too
2. BLOCK - specific address
3. TRAP - trap ID
4. Test.Date - test once a week which has already been represented in WEEK variable
5. Location - combined Longitude and Latitude
6. RESULT - since we already added isPos instead of RESULT as response variable

wnv<- WNV[!is.na(WNV$Wards),-c(3,4,5,7,9,13)]

Observation Sampling:
60% of the total record 14977 are assigned to be training data
40% of the total record 9986 are assigned to be validation data

set.seed(1)  
train.index <- sample(c(1:dim(wnv)[1]), dim(wnv)[1]*0.6)  
train <- wnv[train.index, ]   
valid<- wnv[-train.index, ]

GLM Model Comparison:

GLM 1 lmodel Stepwise regression has 8 predictors with 6568 AIC, 0.9983 sensitivity, and 0.0192 specification.

GLM 2 m2 has 6 number predictors with 6568 AIC, 0.9985 sensitivity and 0.0178 specification.

GLM 3 m3 has 5 number predictors with 6603 AIC, 0.9986 sensitivity and 0.0178 specification.

By looking at the metrics, GLM 3 m3 yeilds the best result.

Lift Chart for best model

The team tried to compute a lift chart for each model. The lift chart area barely changed. So, here we only display the lift chart for our best model.

pred <- predict(m3, valid)
gain <- gains(valid$isPos, pred, groups=100)

plot(c(0,gain$cume.pct.of.total*sum(valid$isPos))~
       c(0,gain$cume.obs), 
     xlab="# cases", ylab="Cumulative", main="", type="l")
lines(c(0,sum(valid$isPos))~c(0, dim(valid)[1]), lty=2)

The best model equation is:

Odds (Probability of Negative/Probability of Positive) =
\(ODDS = e^{-434 + - 5.88*(TRAP_TYPEOVI) - 2.88*(LONGITUDE)+1.08 * (TRAP_TYPEGRAVID) + 0.76* (TRAP_TYPESENTINEL) +0.12* (WEEK)+0.09 * (SEASON.YEAR) + 0.06* (NUMBER.OF.MOSQUITOES)}\)

##Decision Tree

model <-rpart(isPos ~ ., data = train,  method = "class")
# "snipping" off the least important splits - pruning, best prune tree
pruned <- prune(model, cp = model$cptable[which.min(model$cptable[,"xerror"]),"CP"])
prp(pruned, type = 1, extra = 1, split.font = 1, varlen = -10)

Decision tree has only one node. We have tested on oversampling the POSITIVE result in the model and the result still remains the same.
